rca of the issue:
PHONE NORMALIZATION INCONSISTENCY between WRITE and READ paths.

Reproduction:
  1. Login cashier/1234, open shift 500000, scan 8991111000011, F5, pay cash 10000.
  2. In Receipt modal click receipt-send-btn -> SendReceiptModal opens.
  3. Type '08570000123' into send-to-input -> pill is amber 'Belum terdaftar.'
  4. Click send-wa-link-btn (or send-api-btn or send-mailto-btn after switching to email). Sonner toast 'Member baru: M-0005 — PELANGGAN 0123' appears (confirmed in screenshot at /root/.emergent/automation_output/20260622_143055/).
  5. Clear input, re-type '08570000123'. EXPECTED: pill turns green with 'Member M-0005'. ACTUAL: pill stays amber 'Belum terdaftar'.

Root cause (file paths):
  - SendReceiptModal.jsx line 78: `normalizedPhone = to.replace(/[^\d+]/g,'').replace(/^0/,'62')` -> for '08570000123' produces '628570000123'.
  - SendReceiptModal.jsx line 84-86 (ensureMember): builds `contact.phone = '+'+normalizedPhone` -> '+628570000123' and calls api.upsertMemberFromContact.
  - mockApi.js line 88: `db.customers.add({ ..., phone: phone || '' })` -> persists STRING '+628570000123' in IndexedDB.
  - mockApi.js line 39 (lookupCustomer): on re-type the input is '08570000123' (raw). It executes `db.customers.where('phone').equals('08570000123').first()`. Dexie does a strict string equality match; '08570000123' !== '+628570000123' -> returns undefined.
  - The third branch (byEmail) also returns null because no email match.
  - Result: lookupCustomer returns null -> setMemberMatch({customer:null, exists:false}) -> pill renders AMBER.

Mitigation (one-line surgical fix recommended):
Replace mockApi.lookupCustomer body with:
```
async lookupCustomer(q) {
  if (!q) return null;
  const byMember = await db.customers.where('memberNumber').equals(q).first();
  if (byMember) return byMember;
  const norm = (s) => (s||'').replace(/[^\d]/g,'').replace(/^0/, '62');
  const qd = norm(q);
  if (qd) {
    const byPhone = await db.customers.filter(c => norm(c.phone) === qd).first();
    if (byPhone) return byPhone;
  }
  const ql = (q||'').trim().toLowerCase();
  if (ql.includes('@')) {
    const byEmail = await db.customers.filter(c => (c.email||'').toLowerCase() === ql).first();
    if (byEmail) return byEmail;
  }
  return null;
}
```
Apply the same `norm()` helper inside upsertMemberFromContact for the `existing` probe (currently it strips non-digits only — does not coerce leading-0 vs 62) to keep enrol idempotent regardless of what cashier types next time.
